@jannau 
You're correct that that's not nice. But we're doing that for pretty much every device where minor differences are present. After all, pyhomematic just presents an interface for external usage by other apps (HASS for that matter). And HASS in the end takes care of slipping one single platform (climate in this case) over a bunch of technically different devices with similar functionality.
Hiding the internal differences would make the classes more complex, and we'd possibly lose some flexibility as well. So in my opinion the separate classes for different devices (or simliar with internal differences) keep us on the safe side to ensure functionality won't be affected when making changes to just one class.

