@mikekap D'oh, it seems you are correct.  This is the result of some confusion between behaviors of the [BigQuery hadoop connector](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/bigdata-interop/tree/master/bigquery) and the http based bigquery client utilized in luigi.  The intention was to make Hadoop mapreduce jobs that load via the connector atomic using the swap-into-place pattern common throughout luigi, but it seems like when using the bigquery client from the `googleapis` package this is handled by default.  In the case of the connector, intermittent failures between mappers can cause partial uploads to the table, so swap in place via luigi after YARN marks the entire job as successful is the best way to ensure atomicity.

@Tarrasch I think the right way to fix this would be to drop the behavior from the canonical `BigqueryLoadTask` since it is redundant there, but leave the temporary table id generation for task implementors to do swap-in-place if needed.  This would support both use cases.  The target itself could also have a convenience method for doing the swap.

